@node about "About this guide"

This is the documentation for ListServ Version 1.0b2, the second beta release
of ListServ. Like ListServ, this documentation is also in beta and it shares
the version number with ListServ itself. This guide will be expanded and
rewritten if needed for each new release of ListServ. A more detailed guide
will be released with the final version.

The guide is currently arranged into 3 sections, if you read nothing else,
make sure you read at least sections 1 and 2. In fact, ListServ has been
written so that you must read the documentation. This small annoyance will
be removed from the final release, but will be in all beta's. NOBODY can say
that i havent given you ample warning of the dangers of not reading the
documentation. In fact, if you email me asking a question i know is answered
in here, and it is obvious to me that you havent read the documentation, i
will ignore your mail for a while and then just reply with RTFM. If you think
that makes me an unhelpfull bastard, so be it, i just have better things to
do with my time rather then helping people who cant be bothered to read the
documentation. Its these kind of people that slow down the development of
ListServ. Fortunately we havent had anyone like that yet, in fact everyone who
i have spoken to that use it (on IRC and on the test mailing list) are cool
people :)

Hem anyway, i have a tendancy to ramble a bit sometimes, so on with this
guide :)

Last time i say this for a bit ... @{b}READ IT ALL!!!!@{ub}

@endnode

@node req "Requirements"

You will need an Amiga connected to some kind of network allowing mail such
as the Internet. Some method of recieving mail is required, obviously, and
the program used for that MUST be able to make standard RFC822 compliant spool
files, otherwise you will need a program to convert the networks mail files
to RFC822 compliant spool files. For the internet, GetMail on aminet will work
for POP3 recieve, and SMTPd in INetUtils 1.4 (also on aminet) will work for
incomming SMTP mails (Demon users in the UK will need this to recieve mail
anyway).

Some kind of post program is required to send mail to the network, this also
must be RFC822 compliant and be able to handle To, From, Subject fields in
the temporary mailfile (they all can be specified on the command line also),
PutMail and SMTPpost (Aminet and INetUtils 1.4) will work fine for this.

A 24 hour connection is _NOT_ required, as long as some method of storing mail
on your mail server is available, such as a POP3 account or some kind of SMTP
store program running on the mail host (such as mailstore for Demon users).
Normally you wont need to worry about this, your mail host will take care of
that. Please note, web based mail systems that offer free email accounts are
usually unsuitable, as reading and writing is done on the web, and not via
a POP3 account, GeoCities is the only exception I can think of right now.

The ability to create email addresses is preferable, altho it is possible to
run all the mailing lists off one email address, this is both hard to setup and
annoying for the users.

Tip: If you can't create email addresses on your mail host, and you dont
already have an account with GeoCities, get an account there (its free) and
put your list's homepage on there, and use the free email account (POP3) for
your mailing list.  If you already have a GeoCities account, and dont use your
GeoCities email address as your main one, then think about changing your
member name to something suitable for your list and run the list off that.
NOTE: U will probably need a program to strip the crap that GeoCities adds to
mail. 

Demon users will not have a problem with this, as it is very easy to create
email addresses.

Hardware wise, any Amiga running Workbench 2.04+ should be able to handle
it. Memory useage depends on the amount of lists you have, the amount of users
in the current list being processed, and the size of the spool file. The
program itself hardly takes any memory up at all.

@endnode

@node feat "Features"

This is my ToDo list, not all features are implemented yet, and some may not
be done till a later version. I'm always open to suggestions :) Items marked
with a '*' are not yet implemented, items marked with an 'o' are.

For a complete and upto date list of features, please see the home page.

 o Will work with any mail network (a little work may be needed in some cases)
 
 o Amount of mailing lists limited only by memory
 
 * Each mailing list run off 1 email address (optional, u can have a commands
   address and a post address for each list if you want)
 
 * Ability to automatically generate a help file, or use one you have written,
   or both.
 
 o Optionally allow users who haven't subscribed to post to the list (usefull
   for virtual help desks)
 
 o Full logging of commands sent to the list, posts and all mail sent to the
   list (everything is completely optional)
 
 o Ability to change the name of the subscribe, unsubscribe and help commands
 
 o Ability to easily add your own commands to the list. Each mailing list may
   have its own individual commands along with the standard commands
 
 * Each list may be of a different type (discuss or announce)
 
 * Each List may be open or closed, an open list will allow anyone with a
   valid email address to join, and a closed list will only let people join
   once the list owner has verifyed them.
 
 * Each list may be moderated or not, the moderator is settable and doesn't
   have to be the list owner. All mail to the list will be sent to the
   moderator who will read and verify each message and then post it to the
   list.
 
 * Each list may have its own digest, or not, whichever you like. When the
   user subscribes, they set whether they want the digest when it reaches a
   cirtain size which is settable. This is settable by the user only when they
   subscribe or by using the options command.
 
 o If you already have a list of users you want to add to the list, this is
   possible too. ListServ will read a file of RFC822 compliant addresses and
   set the default options of nodigest
 
 * Optionally remove all file attaches from posts
 
 * Optional subscriber limit (not settable by list owner, only by the
   listmaster)
 
 * User aliases, so they can use the list from more then one email address,
   but all mail from the list goes to their one main mail box (except command
   replies)

@endnode

@node config "Configuration"

ListServ's config is pretty easy, however it might seem a little complex to
start with.

The config file is plain ASCII text, lines beginning with a # is a comment.
Blank lines are ignored. The config is made up of commands, some with
arguments and some without. There are only 3 types of argument, a string of
characters (i.e. "abcdefg", "'s are not needed), hereon known as 'string',
boolean (on or off), or integer (a number). The syntax for each line
is <command> [arguments].

The file may be anywhere you like, named anything you like. By default, it
looks in the current directory for ListServ.config, but this may be overridden
with a command line option (see section 5).

For example:

SMTPServer post.demon.co.uk

The command is 'SMTPServer' and the argument is 'post.demon.co.uk' , the
argument in this case is a string.

Logging on

The command here is 'Logging', and the argument 'on'. This time the argument
is a boolean, which can either be 'on' or 'off'. 

DefDigestSize 100

The command here is 'DefDigestSize' and the argument '100'. This argument is
an integer, i.e. a whole number.

EndList

This command takes no arguments.

Each command must be on a single line, you may not have more then one command
on a line. Some commands arguments support 'auto inserts', these are %
followed by a letter, and when found in a string they are replaced with the
equivalent string. The auto inserts supported by commands in the config differ
from command to command, and are documented with the command.

All the configuration commands will now be explained in full. Please note that
altho (almost) all the available configuration options are listed, not all
work as expected yet. I have left out from here the config options that you
cant use properly yet. Please only use documented config options.

Command     : SMTPServer <server>
Argument    : String
Default     : localhost
Description : This specifies the SMTP mail server used for sending mail. It
              takes the server name as an argument.
Limitations : Only outside NewList/EndList pair
Example     : SMTPServer post.demon.co.uk

Command     : MailCommand <command>
Argument    : String
Default     : Inet:C/SMTPpost -f %f <%m
Description : This sets the command used for sending mail. AutoInserts are
              supported in the command. 
              - %m : Mail file (To/Subject filled in)
              - %s : Server name
              - %t : To
              - %f : From
              - %j : Subject
              - %% : Literal %
              
              The string is executed as a normal dos command, as if executed
              from the CLI. Examples for PutMail and SMTPpost are included in
              the example config.
Limitations : Only outside NewList/EndList pair
Example     : MailCommand Inet:C/SMTPpost -f "%f" <%m

Command     : NewList <name>
Argument    : String
Default     : <no default>
Description : Starts a new mailing list. Note that you must end a previous
              list before starting a new one. The name may be anything you
              wish, and is used in the headers generated by ListServ when
              mail is sent to the list, and also used in the commands log.
              The name serves only as an identifier for this list, therefore
              it must be unique. Two lists of the same name will confuse
              ListServ and cause problems when you use the list. There is no
              limit on the characters you can use in the name, or the length
              of it, but for the sake of clarity, keep it short and
              descriptive.
Limitations : Must end previous list before starting a new one
Example     : NewList ListServ Mailing List

Command     : EMail <email address>
Argument    : String
Default     : listmaster@localhost
Description : Specifies the current list's email address. The address must
              be RFC821 compliant, as it is used in the mail headers as the
              address the mail is sent from and also the reply to field unless
              a moderator is used, then the reply to address will be that of
              the moderator. (BETA NOTE: Moderators not yet supported)
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : EMail ListServ Mailing List <listserv@dvalley.demon.co.uk>

Command     : MailPath <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : UUMail:
Description : The path to mail, normally UUMail:. This path is added to the
              beginning of the spoolfile name to create a path to the spool
              file, for example, if the spoolfile name is 'testlist' and the
              mail path is 'UUMail:' then the path to the spoolfile will be
              'UUMail:testlist'. This command is not currently used, and may
              be removed in the future.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : MailPath UUMail:

Command     : ListPath <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/
Description : Sets the path for the datafiles of this list. Namely, the
              User.dat. This is the only datafile *required* to be in the path
              specified here, and it must be unique for each list. It makes
              sense to put your message files and the help file in this path
              as well, altho this is not required. Please note that the data
              files are subject to change.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : ListPath Dh1:Lists/ListServ/

Command     : HelpFile <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/ListHelp.txt
Description : Sets the path to the help file for this list. You may have one
              global helpfile if you like, in which case this should be set to
              the same file for each list. Basically, this is the file
              returned when the 'help' command is sent to the list.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : HelpFile Dh1:Lists/Help.txt

Command     : AutoGenerate <on|off>
Argument    : Boolean
Default     : on
Description : Turns on or off auto generation of the help file. The generated
              text will be appended to the end of the normal help file, and
              will contain details of all the mailing lists available on this
              server and how to join/unjoin all of them, plus the server's
              manager and the list owner and the moderator for each list.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair. Not supported yet.
Example     : AutoGenerate off

Command     : ConfirmMsg <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/Confirm.msg
Description : Sets the path to the confirm message. This is sent back to the
              user when they subscribe to the list. It should contain a short
              welcome message, brief instructions on how to use the list and
              how to request the help file, plus contact addresses.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : ConfirmMsg Dh1:Lists/ListServ/Messages/Confirm.msg

Command     : NoSubscMsg <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/NoSubsc.msg
Description : Sets the path to the 'no subscription' message. This is sent
              back to the user when they try and post and have not subscribed.
              It should contain details of who to contact if they feel the
              message to be in error, for instance, they may be posting from
              an unknown alias address and have already subscribed. Keep it
              brief and to the point. This command is only needed if
              AllowUnkPosts is off.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : NoSubscMsg Dh1:Lists/ListServ/Messages/NoSubsc.msg

Command     : BadSubscMsg <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/BadSubsc.msg
Description : Sets the path to the 'bad subscription' message. This is sent
              back to the user when they send an invalid subscribe or options
              command. It should contain a short description of the subscribe
              and options commands.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : BadSubscMsg Dh1:Lists/ListServ/Messages/BadSubsc.msg

Command     : RemoveMsg <path>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/Remove.msg
Description : Sets the path to the remove message. This is sent back to the
              user when they unsubscribe from the list. It should contain a
              short goodbye message, and instructions on how to rejoin the
              list.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : Remove Dh1:Lists/ListServ/Messages/Remove.msg

Command     : Logging <on|off>
Argument    : Boolean
Default     : on
Description : Turns logging on or off. Finer control of what is logged may be
              achieved with the other logging commands, this is just a master
              switch to turn it on or off. 
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : Logging on

Command     : LogFile <file>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/ListServ.log
Description : Path to the main logfile for this list. If you wish all your
              lists to be logging in one main log file, set the same logfile
              for each list. Please note that this log file will get very big
              with busy lists and it is advisable to use one log file per
              list.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : LogFile Dh1:Lists/ListServ/Logs/MainLog.log

Command     : MailLogFile <file>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/ListServ_Mail.log
Description : The log file used to store mail to the list. It is strongly
              advised that this be a seperate file for each list and be
              different from the main log file for the list. Please note that
              this will get very big very quickly and you may want to turn
              this option off.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : MailLogFile Dh1:Lists/ListServ/Logs/MailLog.log

Command     : LogCommands <on|off>
Argument    : Boolean
Default     : on
Description : This will log all commands sent to the list in the main log. 
              This does NOT include post requests or mail. Commands that are
              logged are: subscribe, remove, help plus any extra commands you
              have defined.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : LogCommands on

Command     : LogPosts <on|off>
Argument    : Boolean
Default     : on
Description : This will log all posts on the list to the main log. This does
              NOT log the actual text of the message, only the address of the
              user that posted. 
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : LogPosts on

Command     : LogMail <on|off>
Argument    : Boolean
Default     : off
Description : This will log all mail (including headers) to the mail log. Only
              incoming mail is logged, and a straight copy of the mail from
              the spoolfile is done. Mails that could not be processed for
              some reason are also logged.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : LogMail on

Command     : AllowUnkPosts <on|off>
Argument    : Boolean
Default     : off
Description : When on, this will allow people who have not subscribed to post
              to the list. You will still have to subscribe to read mail from
              the list however. This is usefull for creating a virtual 'help
              desk'. 
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : AllowUnkPosts off

Command     : DigestDir <dir>
Argument    : String
Default     : Amitcp:ListServ/digest/
Description : Path to digest directory, MUST be a directory
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : DigestDir List:Digest/

Command     : DefDigestSize <size>
Argument    : Integer
Default     : 512
Description : Default digest size (in Kilobytes) .. 0 or 'off' to turn it off
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : DefDigestSize 100

Command     : Subscribe <name>
Argument    : String
Default     : subscribe
Description : Set the string used for the subscribe command. This may not
              contain spaces and must be unique from all other command names.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : Subscribe join

Command     : Remove <name>
Argument    : String
Default     : remove
Description : Set the string used for the remove command. This may not
              contain spaces and must be unique from all other command names.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : Remove unjoin

Command     : Options <name>
Argument    : String
Default     : options
Description : Set the string used for the options command. This may not
              contain spaces and must be unique from all other command names.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : Options opts

Command     : Help <name>
Argument    : String
Default     : help
Description : Set the string used for the help command. This may not
              contain spaces and must be unique from all other command names.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : Help help

Command     : EndList
Argument    : none
Default     : none
Description : End the current list definition. You MUST do this before you
              start a new one.
Limitations : none
Example     : EndList

@endnode

@node extra "Extra Commands"

The previous section contains all the main commands needed to set up a
standard mailing list. However, there comes a time that the standard
subscribe, remove and help commands aren't enough to maintain the mailing
list, you need more, maybe you want to be able to request files or standard
text files, ListServ caters for this with the 'extra commands' feature. It
allows you to create a command to do absolutely anything you want. Whats more,
you can have an unlimited amount with each list, and all the commands are
unique to each list. With this feature, it allows ListServ to be set up as
any kind of server you like, for example, you might want to run a couple of
mailing lists and a file server, this is easy, you just config the 2 lists as
normal, add a new list and disable the subscribe and remove commands, make an
extra command for sending files, and there you go, instant file server. 

The extra configuration commands needed to set this up is as follows.

Command     : NewCmd <name>
Argument    : String
Default     : none
Description : Works a little like NewList, but is for extra commands. This
              sets up a new command, the argument is the name used in the
              subject line as per the standard subscribe etc. commands. 
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : NewCmd send

Command     : DosCmd <cmd>
Argument    : String
Default     : Echo >T:ListServ.TempOut "The list manager is stupid and
                 hasn't configured the list properly*n"
Description : This is the dos command to be executed by ListServ when it gets
              the command. This is used the same as MailCommand, but the
              auto inserts are different.
              - %n : List name
              - %s : Mail server
              - %e : List's EMail address
              - %m : Mail path
              - %l : List path
              - %h : Help file
              - %c : Confirm text file
              - %b : 'Not subscribed' text file
              - %r : Remove text file
              - %g : Logging (on/off)
              - %f : Log file
              - %i : Mail log file
              - %p : Parameters passed to the command by the user
                     (may not exist)
              
              The file specified in 'OutFile' (see below) should be used for
              the output of this command.
Limitations : Only in NewCmd/EndCmd pair
Example     : DosCmd Dh1:Lists/Commands/Send %l %p

Command     : OutFile <file>
Argument    : String
Default     : T:ListServ.TempOut
Description : Specifies the output file of DosCmd. This file has the
              To/From/Subject headers added to the top of it and then mailed
              to the user who sent the command. Sending output to all users
              in the mailing list is not currently supported. The file
              specified here will be deleted after it has been mailed to the
              user.
Limitations : Only in NewCmd/EndCmd pair
Example     : OutFile T:TemporaryOutput

Command     : EndCmd
Argument    : none
Default     : none
Description : End the current command definition. You MUST do this before you
              start a new one.
Limitations : Only in NewList/EndList pair
Example     : EndCmd

Those 4 simple commands will allow you to make a command to do anything you
like. Please note that there is no access restriction on these commands yet
so silly things like 'shell' to run a dos command from email is extremely
stupid because ANYONE would be able to do it. Dont say i didn't warn you.

In order to use this feature to its fullest potential, you will need quite
a lot of knowledge about AmigaDOS scripts or a programming language.
If you dont have that knowledge, then ask in #AmigaCafe on Undernet for
someone who can write you a small script or program to do what you need.

If you come up with some good commands, send me the NewCmd, DosCmd, OutFile
and EndCmd bits from the config (only for the command) and the command you
wrote to do the stuff (if applicable) as i'd like to see what you come up
with.

@endnode

@node run "Running ListServ"

Once you have a config, its time to test it. ListServ supports a few options
on the command line to test your config file. For the sake of this example,
i'll assume your config file is ListServ.config in the current directory.

Open a CLI and type the following into it:

ListServ -d

This will dump your configuration to the CLI. If an error occurs reading the
config, you will be told the line number and the error. Fix the error and
keep trying untill all the problems in the config are fixed.

When you get the config dump, read thru all the output and make sure
everything is set the way you think it should be, if there is a problem, check
the config again. Please note that there are no line numbers in the config
dump because it reads the entire config, processes it, and then dumps it in
a more human readable form then the config itself is in. 

Please note that some extra bits that haven't been covered here may show up
in the config dump, this is normal, just ignore them. They are just
configuration options to allow for the rest of my todo list when i get round
to finishing it.

If your config file is not in the current directory, you will need to specify
where it is, for that you use the option -c. For example:

ListServ -c AmiTCP:db/ListServ.config -d

will dump the config file AmiTCP:db/ListServ.config

Now we have ListServ reading its config properly, we need to see if it works
online. Read the example help file for how to send commands to the list, and
then send a subscribe request to your mailing list. Recieve the mail, then
type in a cli the following to process the mail

ListServ -s uumail:testlist

obviously, replace uumail:testlist with the path and filename of the spoolfile
you just recieved. With any luck, you should get back your welcome message.
Now send a post to the list to test it, then do the same as before to process
the mail and you should see your message echo'd back to you. If you have
problems, check the config, read this document again, then contact me and i'll
try and help. 

Hopefully now you should have your mailing list up and running, now you need
to advertise it and get some users on it. I suggest you have a period of about
a week to a month for testing it just with a few users then go onto grander
things and advertise. I'm not going to attempt to explain how to run a good
mailing list or how to advertise etc, you're on your own now.


@endnode

@node credits "Credits and Contacts"

ListServ was written by Tom Bampton, and is dedicated to Mary-Jane Fortin.
You can contact me by sending mail to fosters@dvalley.demon.co.uk.
The beta mailing list can be joined by sending a message to
testlist@dvalley.demon.co.uk with the subject as:

subscribe "Real Name"

